<p>If we look at the graphs from the previous examples, we can identify some of the properties of exponential functions.</p>

<p>The graphs of <m>f\left(x\right)={2}^{x}</m> and <m>g\left(x\right)={3}^{x}</m>, as well as the graphs of <m>f\left(x\right)={4}^{x}</m> and <m>g\left(x\right)={5}^{x}</m>, all have the same basic shape. This is the shape we expect from an exponential function where <m>b&gt;1</m>.</p>

<p>We notice, that for each function, the graph contains the point <m>\left(0,1\right).</m> This makes sense because <m>{b}^{0}=1</m> for any <m>b&gt;1</m>.</p>

<p>The graph of each function, <m>f\left(x\right)={b}^{x}</m> also contains the point <m>\left(1,b\right).</m> The graph of <m>f\left(x\right)={2}^{x}</m> contains <m>\left(1,2\right)</m> and the graph of <m>g\left(x\right)={3}^{x}</m> contains <m>\left(1,3\right).</m> This makes sense as <m>{b}^{1}=b</m> for any <m>b&gt;1</m>.</p>

<p>Notice too, that the graph of each function <m>f\left(x\right)={b}^{x}</m> also contains the point <m>\left(-1,\frac{1}{b}\right).</m> The graph of <m>f\left(x\right)={2}^{x}</m> contains <m>\left(-1,\frac{1}{2}\right)</m> and the graph of <m>g\left(x\right)={3}^{x}</m> contains <m>\left(-1,\frac{1}{3}\right).</m> This makes sense as <m>{b}^{-1}=\frac{1}{b}</m> for any <m>b&gt;1</m>.</p>

<p>What is the domain for each function? From the graphs we can see that the domain is the set of all real numbers. There is no restriction on the domain. We write the domain in interval notation as <m>(-\infty ,\infty)</m>.</p>

<p>Look at each graph. What is the range of the function? Notice that the graph is always above and never touches the <m>x</m>-axis. Thus, the range is all positive numbers. We write the range in interval notation as <m>\left(0,\infty \right).</m></p>

<p>Whenever a graph of a function approaches a line but never touches it, we call that line an <term>asymptote</term>. For the exponential functions we are looking at, the graph approaches the <m>x</m>-axis very closely but will never cross it. So we call the line <m>y=0,</m> the <m>x</m>-axis, a horizontal asymptote.</p>

<p>We summarize these results below.
